Hic ille est. Cf. note on V. 518. Quoi. This Dative-form, a form still in use in Quintilian's youth (Inst. i. 7. 27), has usually suffered at the hands of copyists. YVhen they recognize that a Dative is required, they change it to cui, otherwise to quo and sometimes qui.

Eun. 848 Sed estne haec Thais, quam uideo? ipsust, 974 Sed estne ille ‘noster Parmeno? et certe ipsus est, or else secl hicine (isne), eg. Ter. Andr. 907 sed hicz'nest Simo 3, Mero. 598 Sed isne est quem currentem uideo? ipsus est. Kaempf suggests Sed Eryscsilusnest, rightly objecting to the form Eryasz'lustne (which would make the line an Anapaestic Dimeter), as hardly Plautine. The line would become an Acatalectic Bacchiae Tetrameter by the addition uideo? <ipsust> or <ib-6> uideo or <eyo> uideo.

789. conlecto. Mart. vn. xxxiii. 4 collzye togam. (See note on v. 779.)

790. The MSS. offer a ‘contracted' bacchiac line, which is not out of keeping with the conclusion of a bac-chiac passage (see note on V. 785). At the same time Schoell's addition of moram, ‘foolish,' which makes an acatalectic Tetrameter, is very likely to be right. If Plautus wrote moram ‘moram the probability of one of the two similar neighbouring words being lost would be very great indeed. Age hanc rem, a variety of the usual lzoc aye.
